snippet.textDisplay: My garage is a rightbrain versus leftbrain juxtaposition of color. I just bought a brand new 2020 Subaru Outback XT Touring in their 'Magnetilite" (anthracite) color, which is fairly boring, but I still have my 2010 KIA Soul Sport in Molten Lava (bright red), with a two tone red and charcoal interior. That car had a freaking red dashboard in it! The KIA Soul and Dodge muscle cars were the most colorful of the last decade. But, we are now in darker times and the Subaru will blend in well with these times of darkness...

snippet.textDisplay: I actually miss the darker and more bland colors of the mid 80s to mid 00s, not the brighter ones : dark green, dark red, dark blue, beige and tan. They always gave me a modest, yet classy vibe to them, even back when they were newer. Now I always call them retro colors. I've seen a lot of VW, Mercedes, BMW and Audi painted like that as a kid back in the 90s and they stuck with me. With the exception of black, silver and white, I actually find today's color options brighter.

snippet.textDisplay: Personally, I like shades of blue, purple, and red. Of course, none of these colors seem available on modern cars from the factory. I have an old pickup in a lovely shade of blue and a daily driver in a decent shade of red. The truck is 35 years old, the daily driver is 19. This all being said, I once saw a bass boat with a blue metallic paint job that I fell in love with. If I ever could, I would paint my truck in that way. However, to even allow it, I would have to essentially take the truck down to the frame, fix all the imperfections, dents, rust, etc, then paint everything perfectly because if I'm going through all that effort, it better be perfect.

snippet.textDisplay: Cars in general are more boring now. Back in the day you could choose every single option on that car including rear axle, transmissions, engine size and there were 8 to 10 options of each. Now it’s just one engine maybe two if you’re lucky, the same transmission and five colors. People used to have a choice and had customization available, their car was a true image of their creativity. Nowadays a car is just a cookie cutter stamp out that costs four times as much.

snippet.textDisplay: Making colored paint doesn't cost more than making boring paint. Other than red which is notorious for fading making a color doesn't cost any more, but with each new color they have to spend a lot of money in testing to ensure it won't fade. For example it might cost a car company $500,000 to do the testing for one color, it costs $500,000 for black, $500,000 for blue, $500,000 for pink, so they cut out less common color options to save costs. Just go to maaco and ask how much it will cost to paint your car orange vs white. Also the paint itself isn't expensive, that's why maaco charges the same for an f350 as a miata. Car companies just jack up prices because they can. Corvettes come in two reds one is bright and is free, the other is dark and costs an extra $995, the paint costs the same, but they put a second layer of clear coat on it and charge you for it, and people pay.
